# RFdiffusion All-Atom / RFDiffusionAA isolated runtime

Backend name used by this stack: `rfdiffusion_all_atom_legacy`

This is an experimental backbone-generation backend and is intentionally kept
separate from the stable RFdiffusion v1 `rfdiffusion-se3nv` conda environment.

## Source

```text
Repository: https://github.com/baker-laboratory/rf_diffusion_all_atom.git
Local path: ~/protein_design/repos/rf_diffusion_all_atom
Commit tested/installed: f913a19e16f30858ce7a724fe028475b1871319c
Submodule: lib/rf2aa -> https://github.com/baker-laboratory/RoseTTAFold-All-Atom.git
Submodule commit: f87f5b8cdf1a68a7d4fa8c44300197944698a995
License: BSD License, University of Washington, 2024
```

The public repository README calls this tool "RFDiffusion AA". It is not the
RosettaCommons Foundry RFD3/RFdiffusion3 model. Foundry RFD3 is installed and
documented separately in `envs/foundry_rfd3.env` and
`docs/foundry_rfd3_backend_report.md`.

## Runtime Artifacts

```text
Container: ~/protein_design/containers/rf_se3_diffusion.sif
Container URL: http://files.ipd.uw.edu/pub/RF-All-Atom/containers/rf_se3_diffusion.sif
Weight file: ~/protein_design/weights/RFDiffusionAA_paper_weights.pt
Weight URL: http://files.ipd.uw.edu/pub/RF-All-Atom/weights/RFDiffusionAA_paper_weights.pt
```

The source license states that it covers both the source code and model weights
referenced by the README.

## Entry Point

RFDiffusionAA is run through the upstream Apptainer container:

```bash
apptainer run --nv ~/protein_design/containers/rf_se3_diffusion.sif \
  -u run_inference.py \
  inference.ckpt_path=~/protein_design/weights/RFDiffusionAA_paper_weights.pt \
  inference.input_pdb=~/protein_design/examples/epitope_scaffold/input/5TPN.pdb \
  inference.output_prefix=$PWD/rfdiffusion_outputs/design \
  'contigmap.contigs=["10-40,A163-181,10-40"]' \
  inference.num_designs=1
```

The upstream contig syntax uses comma-separated contigs inside a list string,
for example `["10-40,A163-181,10-40"]`. This differs from RFdiffusion v1's
`[10-40/A163-181/10-40]` syntax.

## Integration Notes

- Use `BACKBONE_BACKEND=rfdiffusion_all_atom_legacy` with
  `scripts/slurm_templates/run_backbone_generation.sbatch`.
- Outputs are normalized to `rfdiffusion_outputs/design_0.pdb`,
  `design_0.trb`, and `backbone_list.txt`.
- RFDiffusionAA may write a `.trb` file containing contig mappings. When the
  ligand-free fallback is used, the stack generates a compatible `.trb` with
  `scripts/make_motif_mapping_from_sequence.py`, so the existing
  `scripts/make_fixed_positions_jsonl.py` can map motif residues for
  ProteinMPNN fixed-position design.
- In ligand-free protein motif tests, upstream RFDiffusionAA can finish
  denoising but fail during `idealize_backbone.rewrite` because that helper
  asserts exactly one ligand. The stack launcher therefore supports
  `LEGACY_AA_ALLOW_UNIDEALIZED_FALLBACK=1`: it copies `unidealized/design_N.pdb` to
  the normalized output path and runs `scripts/make_motif_mapping_from_sequence.py`
  to generate a compatible `.trb` mapping from the exact motif sequence.
- For ligand-free motif batches, the launcher runs RFDiffusionAA as a loop of
  `inference.num_designs=1` calls with increasing `inference.design_startnum`.
  This prevents the upstream idealization failure after one design from
  truncating the rest of the batch.
- RFdiffusion v1 remains the stable baseline; this backend is experimental.
